manifest:TextObject.manifest:TextString: The Warner Bros. and Legendary logos have Kryptonian carving on their edges.
The look of the master shots in the "birth of Kal-El scene" was partially inspired by the Tenebrism of Italian Baroque paintings, especially Artemisia Gentileschi's "Judith Slaying Holofernes."
Ruins of the previous Kryptonian age are in the background of every shot of the planet.
Each council member represents a guild of Krypton.
Each guild member chair is carved with various Kryptonian phrases that are unique to that particular guild.
The weapons are covered in poetry and have been passed down in each family/guild.
Robots are in families/guilds for generations and are older than their masters.
Armor is also ancient and handed down through generations.
The Codex is like Lucy - a proto-Kryptonian being.
The voice of the Kryptonian warning announcements is Henry Cavill.

Writer and artist John Byrne reimagined Kryptonian society for his mythology reboot series The Man of Steel, showing a colder, more emotionally detached society than had been depicted before, one that had dominated its home planet to the point of collapse.

The skull shown in the liquid geo display is proto-human - more Cro-Magnon than Homo sapiens - the data being 20,000 years old as relayed from the Scout Ship we will see later buried in the ice on Earth.
The proto-Kryptonian is now inside Kal-El's genes.
The Command Key becomes an integral plot point throughout the movie.
Kryptonian weapons are treated within the culture as ancient artifacts and family heirlooms; they are not mass-produced.
There are personal robots with the other council members watching the sentencing, like pages in medieval times.
The sun is a red dwarf star in the movie. In the comics, it was a red giant.
The violin soloist is playing a Stradivarius built in 1728, one of the rarest instruments in the world.
The core has been ignited, and now the planet is becoming a failed sun, or neutron star.
The Debbie Sue is a trawler. The average number of crewmembers on a crab boat is 5-10. Crabbing is considered one of the most dangerous jobs in the world.
The tank set was the largest underwater green screen ever built.
The two whales are the last of their species - extinction binds them to Clark.
The girl across from Clark in the school bus is Lana Lang. In the comics, Lana Lang is Clark's love interest.
The stuntman who played Nam-Ek, Mike Justus, is also the same person driving the car.

The depiction of the Kents in Man of Steel harkens back to the very first page of Superman #1 and what the as-yet unnamed adoptive parents say to young Clark. "Now listen to me, Clark! This great strength of yours - you've got to hide it from people or they'll be scared of you!" "But when the proper time comes, you must use it to assist humanity."

The scene where Jonathan shows Clark the spacecraft was partially inspired by the limited-series comic Superman: Secret Origin, in which young Clark tearfully says, "I want to be Clark Kent. I want to be your son," to which Jonathan responds, "Clark...You are my son."
The 1986 limited series The Man of Steel changed many elements of the classic Superman mythology, including having both of his adoptive parents remaining alive well into Clark's adult life.

In the 2003/2004 limited series Superman: Birthright, Clark Kent travels the world not knowing his own background/heritage, while trying to use his powers to help people without revealing himself, similar to in the movie.
Alessandro Juliani ("Officer Sekowsky") portrayed Dr. Emil Hamilton on Smallville. He also appeared in Watchmen.
The picture that Lois takes on her camera of Clark walking on the ice-shelf wall was inspired by blurry photos of Bigfoot.
Robots have been keeping the Scout Ship running for over 20,000 years.
Lois' scared first reaction to Clark in the Scout Ship recalls what Superman says to the reporter in their first meeting in Action Comics #1: "You needn't be afraid of me. I won't harm you."
The scene when Dr. Manhattan is discovered to have escaped to Mars in Zack Snyder's film Watchmen inspired the landscape on the military computer's screen.
The polar bear is a reminder that Clark, like the bear, is an endangered species - the last of his kind.
ï¿¼ The voice of the Scout Ship computer is that of Carla Gugino, who played Sally Jupiter in Watchmen.
The visual style of the Kryptonian history lesson in liquid geo is influenced by a mix of Soviet and bas-relief art.
The longest visual effects shot in the movie is the history lesson of Krypton that Jor-El explains to Clark as the camera continually pans and pivots around the room (it is 90 seconds long).
It took five months of careful preparation to figure out how to build the Superman suit.
Jor-El gets the classic "S" reveal of pulling back his cloak in this scene.
Each Superman suit would require 20 different artisans from four costuming companies to create.
Each Superman cape required 14 3/4 yards of ultrasuede fabric to create.
There were 14 Superman suits made for Man of Steel.
When Superman flies, he's manipulating space and gravity because of the effect the sun and earth have on him.
Each sonic boom = Mach speed.
Amy Adams' auburn-haired Lois Lane is a departure for the typically brunette or raven-haired character.
As in the movie, a tornado threatens Smallville in the 1998 limited-series comic Superman For All Seasons.
In Superman: Earth One, Jonathan dies while Clark is still growing up, leaving the young man conflicted over how to honor his late adoptive father's wishes for how he should use his abilities.

Lois and Perry's contentious but mutually respectful relationship has its basis in the comics, such as in Superman: Birthright, which shows Perry making a list of reasons why and why not to fire Lois.
The LexCorp truck that drops Clark off reads "Better Farming Through Science," alluding to Lex Luthor's character as having a brilliant, if misguided, scientific mind.
The farmland surrounding the Kent Farm location was due to grow soy that year, so production arranged to grow corn and timed the planting so the corn could be the correct height during filming.
The Black Zero looks like the International Space Station when tracked from the ground.

The earliest depictions of Krypton, in the Superman newspaper strips of 1939, described its inhabitants as being a "civilization of supermen - beings which represent the human race at its ultimate peak of perfect development!"
Plato's The Republic discusses the meaning of justice, the theory of forms and the immortality of the soul, among other philosophical topics.
The Smallville High School sports team name is The Spartans, in homage to 300.
Sullivan's Truck & Tractor Repair is a reference to the TV series Smallville.
The stained glass image behind Clark depicts the biblical story of Jesus in the Garden of Gethsemane.
In the 2010 graphic novel Superman: Earth One volume one, Clark's first public appearance as Superman is when an invading alien force threatens to destroy Earth, as in the movie.
Although there have been variations through the years, the red, blue and yellow color scheme of Superman's costume dates back to the first Action Comic in 1938.
All of the military personnel are real-life airmen, guardsmen, sailors and soldiers who each had at least one deployment to Iraq or Afghanistan.
The first Faora, Faora Hu-Ul, was introduced in Action Comics #471 and #472 in 1977.
DC Comics killed Superman in Superman #75 (1993).
The character of Tor-An is played by Richard Cetrone, who has appeared in all but one of Mr. Snyder's films.
Superman famously wore a black and silver costume when he returned from the dead in 1993, except with a longer hairstyle and no cape.
The straps restraining Kal-El are made of liquid geo, just like the display screens throughout Krypton.

The Command Key that Jor-El sends to help educate and guide his son in the film has a variety of comic book counterparts, such as the historical chronicle tablet in Superman: Birthright, and the sunstone crystal in Superman: Secret Origin.
The character of Jax-Ur, portrayed in the film by Mackenzie Grey, first appeared in Adventure Comics #289 (1961).
The twinkle of light behind Kal-El when he flies away is Jor-El blinking out/unplugging from the ship's systems.
Kryptonian plasma is left on Earth when the escape pod crashes in the cornfield.

During the Smallville battle, a hot dog truck can be seen three times making its way across town. It first appears by the Kent Farm as Superman tackles Zod near the grain silos; it then appears outside the IHOP windows as Faora and Superman trade blows; finally, as the Dropship lands to pick up Faora and Nam-Ek, the hot dog truck arrives at the far end of the street. A miniature version of this truck now sits in the Cruel and Unusual Films office.
When Zod's helmet breaks, it harks back to young Clark's X-ray vision fright.
Heat vision comes from an internal source, hence the sub-surface glow that is visible under Zod's skin when he uses it. This is not an easy power to use, as it does cause some discomfort.
Superman is famously more powerful than a locomotive.

The Black Zero at the start of the film is very clean. By the time Zod arrives on Earth, it has been retrofitted and the three triangular sections of the Phantom Zone generator can be seen attached to the "shoulders" of the Black Zero.
The debris cloud ejected from the top of the World Engine was referenced from images of the volcano EyjafjallajoÌˆkull in Iceland.
A gravitational singularity, or space-time singularity, is thought to have infinite gravity.
Original white-board sketch (May 2011) of World Engine with the gravity beam pounding the ground.

Metropolis is an amalgam of Los Angeles, New York and Chicago, with landmark buildings removed. When rendered digitally by Double Negative, Metropolis comprised 32 square miles of CG buildings and streets.
The defense mechanisms at work here are the same liquid geo technology seen in display screens throughout Krypton.
Richard Schiff's Dr. Emil Hamilton works for S.T.A.R. Labs, a DC Comics reference.
When Kal-El hovers across the crater to Zod, it is a Dr. Manhattan moment, in homage to Watchmen.

The second longest visual effects shot in the film is Zod on his knees, explaining how Superman has taken everything from him. Michael's performance was so good that his speech was played in one long take.
Blaze Comics is a cryptic reference from the Superman canon.
Here is the original (April 2011) white-board drawing, by Zack Snyder, of Zod swinging the I-beam at Superman, while Superman shoots his heat vision at it.
The "Utopia Casino" sign is a possible tease of a villain from the comics, Tony Gallo.
A Wayne Industries satellite hints at future storylines.
LexCorp is visible on the side of the building, referencing another villain from the canon.
The statues that are struck are Truth and Justice. Truth falls.
A Reaper drone does not cost $12 million, as stated by General Swanwick - its estimated flyaway cost is closer to $17 million.
The Daily Planet's iconic globe has typically been situated on the rooftop of its building.
